<!-- Intro Container -->
<div class="w3-container" id="intro">
  <div class="w3-content" style="max-width:850px">
    <h5 class="w3-center w3-padding-64"><span class="w3-tag w3-wide">IOT INTRODUCTION</span></h5>
    <p>The concept of Internet of Things (IoT) was first introduced in 1999 and has been called the third wave of the world's information industry development after computers and the Internet, and has been developed for more than 20 years now. Nowadays, in our daily life, we can already come into contact with very many IoT products, such as various smart home appliances, smart door locks, etc. These are all relatively mature applications of IoT technology.</p>
    <br>
    <h5 style="font-size:16px"><span class="w3-tag w3-wide w3-grey w3-text-white"><strong>IOT IS ALSO THE INTERNET</strong></span></h5>
    <p class="w3-text-grey" style="text-align:justify;font-size:18px">The Internet of Things uses the infrastructure of the Internet as a carrier of information, i.e. modern IoT products must be "things" that are connected to the Internet in some way, and "things" that upload/download data and interact with people via the Internet.</p>

    <h5 style="font-size:16px"><span class="w3-tag w3-wide w3-grey w3-text-white"><strong>IOT IS ALL ABOUT "THINGS"</strong></span></h5>
    <p class="w3-text-grey" style="text-align:justify;font-size:18px">Modern IoT applications are a kind of Internet application, but there is a big difference between IoT applications and traditional Internet applications, that is, the subject of traditional Internet production and consumption of data is human, while the subject of modern IoT production and consumption of data is things. In modern IoT application scenarios, the producers of data are "things", such as smart devices or sensors, and the consumers of data are often also "things".</p>

    <h5 style="font-size:16px"><span class="w3-tag w3-wide w3-grey w3-text-white"><strong>IOT AND AI</strong></span></h5>
    <p class="w3-text-grey" style="text-align:justify;font-size:18px">Artificial intelligence is arguably one of the hottest words in IT in recent years. Looking at the development path of artificial intelligence, we can see that there are two main reasons why the development of artificial intelligence has been able to advance by leaps and bounds.</p>
    <ul>
      <li class="w3-text-grey" style="text-align:justify;font-size:18px">The development of hardware has enabled the learning time of deep learning neural networks to be rapidly reduced.</li>
      <li class="w3-text-grey" style="text-align:justify;font-size:18px">In the age of big data, the cost of acquiring large amounts of data has become lower.</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="w3-text-grey" style="text-align:justify;font-size:18px">In fact, the second reason is particularly important. Neural networks, by their very nature, require huge amounts of data to learn, and the amount of effective data available for learning often determines the effectiveness of the final trained neural network, even the importance of the algorithm can be ranked after the amount of data. IoT devices, such as smart home appliances and wearable devices, generate huge amounts of data every day, which, after being processed and cleaned, can be used as good training data to feed the neural network. At the same time, the trained neural network can be reapplied to IoT devices, thus forming a virtuous cycle.</p>
    <br>

    <div class="w3-panel w3-leftbar" style="background-color:#F5F5F5">
      <p><i>"IoT technologies are appearing and approaching our lives far earlier than we would expect."</i></p>
      <blockquote class="twitter-tweet"><p lang="en" dir="ltr">The future of <a href="https://twitter.com/hashtag/AI?src=hash&amp;ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw">#AI</a> is on the <a href="https://twitter.com/hashtag/Edge?src=hash&amp;ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw">#Edge</a>. Here is the Impact Radar of Edge AI per <a href="https://twitter.com/Gartner_inc?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw">@Gartner_inc</a> The use cases range from autonomous vehicles, robots and drones to streaming analytics to tiny code on consumer devices for wake words.<a href="https://twitter.com/hashtag/CloudComputing?src=hash&amp;ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw">#CloudComputing</a> <a href="https://twitter.com/hashtag/DataScientists?src=hash&amp;ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw">#DataScientists</a> <a href="https://twitter.com/hashtag/CIO?src=hash&amp;ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw">#CIO</a> <a href="https://twitter.com/hashtag/cto?src=hash&amp;ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw">#cto</a> <a href="https://twitter.com/hashtag/IoT?src=hash&amp;ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw">#IoT</a> <a href="https://t.co/3tTXuIHquz">pic.twitter.com/3tTXuIHquz</a></p>&mdash; Helen Yu (@YuHelenYu) <a href="https://twitter.com/YuHelenYu/status/1472816226938331146?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw">December 20, 2021</a></blockquote> <script async src="https://platform.twitter.com/widgets.js" charset="utf-8"></script>
