      <h5 style="font-size:16px"><span class="w3-tag w3-wide w3-grey w3-text-white"><strong>SENTIMENT ANALYSIS</strong></span></h5><br>
      <img class="w3-left" style="max-width:670px" src="wordcloud.svg" alt="50 IoT texts">
      <p class="w3-text-grey">A wordcloud with the top words in this set of tweets using #IoT, was created using the wordclouds.com tool. Using the top 200 tweets, words with frequent use and association with tweets about #nhs emerged. These top words (with frequency of word use) could make up a generic crossword-type sentence on the aspect of IoT that people are interested in as a technology: stock(140), bigdata(88), ai(73), dividend(68), stockmarket(68), mhealth(38), socialmedia(38), healthtech(38).</p>
      <br><p><span class="w3-tag w3-grey w3-text-white">Second wordcloud with frequency count</span></p>
      <img src="second wordcloud.png" alt="second wordcloud" style="width: 100%">
      <p class="w3-text-grey">A second wordcloud analysis using the top 200 tweets was performed on tagcrowd.com which allowed more control on functions such as grouping associated words, minimising articles/common verbs, and drawing out co-hashtags. This second wordcloud led to more illustrative words that linked to associated themes found in the analysis of full tweet texts.
        <br>We can tell that the highest keywords continue to revolve around areas such as finance, health and media, which is a side-effect of the fact that the development of IoT in these areas is most valued. Words such as stocks(140) and investing(63) were the most mentioned in the tweets, <strong style="color:#CD5C5C">and people's concern for money is something that technological change will not change.</strong>
        <br>Interestingly, China appears frequently in the keywords, is it possible that the development of IoT in China is gaining importance?</p>

      <hr /><br>


