      <p class="w3-text-grey">Of the 5,448 users, 1,918 have information about geographic location, which represents 35% of the total users. I have selected the top six geographic locations and it is clear that India accounts for a large proportion of the tweets. What's more, Rio de Janeiro in Brazil and Kingdom of Saudi Arabia are the second and third most tweeted city. But because people can name their location as they wish, Internet(791), Worldwide(348), and Earth(319) also appear in the top positions.<br>Looking at the bar chart and the map I find that two very different messages are presented. The map shows that Europe and the USA have significantly more tweeting accounts than any other continent, but if we look at the bar chart alone it is difficult to see the developed regions.</p><hr />

      <br>
      <h5 style="font-size:16px"><span class="w3-tag w3-wide w3-grey w3-text-white"><strong>DEMOGRAPHICS</strong></span></h5>
      <br>
      <iframe title="" aria-label="Column Chart" id="datawrapper-chart-PCR8S" src="https://datawrapper.dwcdn.net/PCR8S/2/" scrolling="no" frameborder="0" style="width: 0; min-width: 100% !important; border: none;" height="480"></iframe><script type="text/javascript">!function(){"use strict";window.addEventListener("message",(function(e){if(void 0!==e.data["datawrapper-height"]){var t=document.querySelectorAll("iframe");for(var a in e.data["datawrapper-height"])for(var r=0;r<t.length;r++){if(t[r].contentWindow===e.source)t[r].style.height=e.data["datawrapper-height"][a]+"px"}}}))}();
      </script>
      <p class="w3-text-grey">Demographics can help us better understand which areas and which demographics are more followed when following IoT topics, but unfortunately none of the Twitter accounts provide private information such as their age and country of residence. So I sorted users by their number of friends: over 1,000,000, between 1,000,000 and 100,000, and less than 100,000. Ten of them had more than 1,000,000 friends, so I browsed their Twitter accounts in general.
      Most of these accounts are CEOs of companies, professors, writers, consultants, etc.</p>
    </div>
    <br>



<!-- Discussion Container -->
  <div class="w3-container" id="discussion" style="padding-bottom:32px;">
    <div class="w3-content" style="max-width:850px">
      <h5 class="w3-center w3-padding-48"><span class="w3-tag w3-wide">Topic discussion</span></h5>
      <p><span class="w3-tag">Above all,</span> this article attempts to clear the fog on the mysterious and widely known IoT space, using collected Twitter data to show us what the leading talking heads are looking at in IoT right now, and to show us that bots are also a great way to help people get the fastest and most focused information about it. What's more, people are no longer confined to indoor IoT, but are also looking at security systems, help with out-of-door parking, multimodal charging devices and more. More thoughtfully, Alexa or other intelligent voice assistants are rarely mentioned in tweets, perhaps because people think that asking for the weather, the time and requesting music is a rare occurrence?</p>
